<review>Was visiting from out of state, so it was my first time ordering food from Thai Time Bistro. Ordered the Avocado Curry, it was very delicious. Nice big chunks of fresh Avocado, lots of red and green peppers with plenty of chicken and several shrimp.
Patrick was the fella that took my order, he was very friendly with everyone that was placing an order or there for pickup orders.
If I lived near by, I would most definitely choose to order food from Thai Time Bistro often.<//review></record></dataset><record>

<Text>Unfortunately after changing managers I had to change a once excellent review. Thai Time Bistro in Ocean Beach does not have consistency among chefs. Before the old chef took over as manager you could order any dish without fish sauce. Now you can only get those dishes without fish sauce when she is there. So vegan options are very limited. They also don't tell you there is fish sauce in things when you order a vegetarian option. You must inquire each visit, and ask if you can get it without the fish sauce. The manager told me any of the chefs can prepare the dish without fish sauce. But I have been told repeatedly by other wait staff that getting items without fish sauce is not an option for the chef that is cooking. I have spoken to them multiple times telling them cohesion is really important. But they basically told me that they are not catering to vegetarians or vegans. So I figured a shout out was important. I won't be eating there anymore. Unfortunately there isn't another Thai place in walking distance :(<//Text><pics>None</pics><Response>None< /Response>< gmapID>

< text>
This place is good, we sometimes stop by for lunch. Our usual orders are the Panang curry , the pad thai, and the beef noodles. For lunch they have combos with an entree, a soup & salad, and an egg roll for $12 or up to $16 depending on the meat you order with it.

Update 4/20/18

Owners have changed, food took too long to bring out (some of our party got their food 45 min after us) and the recipes are different as well. Got my usual Pad Thai and there was just no flavor. Can't recommend anymore.<//text>

<Name>Bobo Link</Name>< review>
The good: I used GrubHub  to order, and my order arrived 15 minutes before expected. Food was a perfect temperature to dive right in.
The okay: The crab angel appetizers were just slightly overcooked,  a bit too brown at the edges. And with a subtle but odd salty taste.
The not so good: I noted on order that I wanted MILD, not spicy. My panang curry is definitely spicy, probably moderately spiced for some, but too spicy for me.  I also asked that the driver call when he arrived, so I was startled when there was a knock and no call.
I have eaten at all the Thai Time restaurants in San Diego,  always enjoy the food. But they went just a little off mark with this online order.< /review>

< Text>
#buyerbeware

I am super annoyed with Restoration Hardware. After spending $3000 on a ‚Äúsolid wood‚Äù table, the top vener gummed up with regular wear and tear. I am so sad I didn‚Äôt take a picture of that! It looked terrible, so we had to cover it with a table cloth. They would not replace it even though we notified them within 30 days of purchasing. They said it was not defective, but our fault for damaging the table. The problem was that the table continued to be damaged by just placing plates and utensils on it. They also recommended a repair kit, which we purchased, but was completely useless. So we decided to refinish it, Since we thought it was solid wood. We should have been able to stand down a layer or two and get to something that we could stain. Instead we spent hours of standing through multiple veneers to get through to the very last layer, which is pieces of plywood put together and not solid wood. I am super disappointed in Restoration Hardware because they are not an inexpensive brand and I thought they were higher quality, but clearly they are not. So frustrating.

< review>
RE: RH online customer service. I wanted to buy a couch in a stocked fabric so I could return it (and just forfeit the shipping cost) if I didn't like it. I found several couches and fabric choices that qualified. However, I chose "down-feather" instead of the "standard" fill choice, and didn't notice that the couch no longer qualified as stock and instead entered into the "you lose 50% + tax" of the cost of the couch if you return it category. It is my fault for breezing through the page that agreed with the return policy. I bought the couch, then realized what had happened. I called customer service the next day. The first customer service rep was pushy about there being nothing that could be done, stating, "are you sure you want to talk to a manager even though there is nothing they can do?", to which I said yes. The manager then said she could reach out to the manufacturer who declined the request to cancel the order, before they even started making it. We recently received the couch, and it is an eye-sore, which I will be returning. However hard you try to fluff and smooth the pillows, they look nothing like the photo of the Cloud Two-Seat Cushion Sofa. I am disappointed in my mistake, for one, and that RH could not help. Perhaps if they had a higher quality of customer service, I wouldn't have lost over $3,000 as a result.</review>

< Review>
I drove 40 minutes from my home to purchase a sofa along with pillows and two chairs. I walked through the doors and was greeted by...not a single soul. <Review>First, let me say that I have never left a review before, but felt absolutely compelled after seeing some people that had a negative experience. I hope that someone sees this when they are trying to find a place when they are in as tough of a spot as I was.

Dr. Madearis is an absolute gem. She is kind, thorough and really explained things in a manner that was easy for me to understand. It's nice to feel like you are included in the process of treating your pet. The communication from the clinic as a whole was very good, even in the pandemic, when they have a bunch of excuses for not being communicative.

It wasn't cheap. But it was worth it to get my cat back and good health. They did that and made me feel like Topper was in great hands the whole time. So much so, that she will be going there in the future regardless of the price. Thanks, from both of us!< /Review>< Pics>

They insisted keeping him. I am currently a vet tech student and its against the law for animal hospitals to keep the animal from the family if they decide to deny care for them at the facility. So they kept insisting keeping him and offered us to put him down. Which costed us more money. Another $750 so they can sedate and put him to sleep.  After waiting a whole  8 hours of the situation, the decision was made to put him to sleep. ( which we could have done somewhere else that was cheaper). It was until 5:30pm we said our last goodbyes to our dog. Anyways, this place only wants you for the money. They do not care about the animals here. We wanted to take him somewhere else but they insisted keeping him (which is illegal if the owner wants the animal back). We also came to bring a stray cat today  because he has a patch of skin off from his left side off. You can see the cats flesh muscles. It looks really bad. We waited for 45mins and seen the vet assistants avoiding our car (that was there first before any other cars arrived) and they never came to see the cats condition. Which I thought was very wrong because vet hospitals should care for the animals as their slogan says. Overall, I hope you guys fix your system. Its uncalled for to charge ridiculous amount of money to help and care for animals. However, I took financial responsibility for her and I'm so glad that I did. Some people think the costs are too high here but you have to keep in mind it's an emergency hospital. These people are working around-the-clock. And I can't speak for everyone but the staff there that I dealt with were very compassionate and responsive. I have 2 dogs at home that I will now start taking to Dr Klomhaus.  Happy ending, the little husky I found that was torn apart from this German shepherd is doing very well. And I have found a safe home for her. All is well because of this hospital and wonderful doctor and staff.</review>

< text>
Knowing only that my cat, Chester, was in serious distress, I took him to VCA as an emergency. It was quite busy, therefore a bit of a wait and it took a few tries to get through to let them know we'd arrived.  Considering the volume of patients they had, I still feel we were dealt with in a timely manner. (A staff member even brought cold bottled water out for those of us waiting in parking lot.) The staff that I had interactions with and those I observed were all professional and caring. And as busy as they were - they LISTENED.
Dr. Klomhaus - himself - called me and explained the issue and the gravity of the situation.  He was straightforward with his questions, explanations and suggestions. I know that it mattered to him that I understood, and I appreciate that more than I can say.
I was very worried about the fact that I knew that this was going to cost more than I had, and I let them know right away. Instead of turning us away, Dr.Klomhaus gave me a (deeply) discounted bill and Chester came home with the medicine and prescription food that he needed.
I thank God for Dr.Klomhaus and thank Dr.Klomhaus and crew for saving my cat.<//text>

< Text>
We took in our Pit Bull Terrier after she had been attacked by our other dog which left her a wound on her neck that looked inflamed. When we took her in, the vet (Kristi Medearis) came in and began to explain to us what she found/assumed she found. She went through the options. She told my mother and I that she recommended surgery to go in and check out the wound because there might be separation of skin from fat/muscle, or something along those lines, or that she could euthanize the dog. When she suggested we could euthanize her, she said it with a casualness that showed no empathy or compassion for our pet or for how afraid we were. The offer for euthanasia was given before she even knew what was truly wrong with her. The operation was estimated to be around two to three thousand dollars, something we could not afford so we opted to simply take antibiotics for her and hope for the best at home, given the circumstances. Before she was brought out to us, they said they had wrapped her neck with something to protect it and charged us almost forty dollars for gauze and self-adhering wrap. It's been a week and a day and Raven (our dog) is healing well, her neck no longer swollen and the bite only a scab now. She still has scabs where they shaved her neck, and we can only assume they shaved her haphazardly, with indifference and/or lack of skill. All in all, the place is only there for the money. They do not try to work with the human of the animal with payment plans unless you qualify for CareCredit. If you have an emergency and absolutely need a twenty-four hour vet, then go ahead, but don't come here if you don't have to. < Review>
Two months ago, my terrier mix was bitten by a Green Mojave Rattlesnake.  We arrived at VCA in Indio at 1am and they rushed Elmer to the treatment room. He was near death and I was given no false hope by the staff. All of his systems and organs were crashing. I never felt pressured from anyone at VCA to pursue treatment. If fact, one vet sympathetically told me that, even though Elmer's part of my family, treatment would be costly and even if the dog survived, there were quality of life issues to consider after a snakebite. I appreciated his frankness.

I pretty much said my goodbyes to Elmer during the one hour drive to the hospital, but for my own peace of mind, I decided to give him one round of antivenom just so that I could say I gave him a fighting chance. He's one tough dog. Although he was in a coma, his blood work showed marked improvement after the first treatment so we gave him another, then another. He remained in critical care for 5 days and to my delight and amazement, I was able to bring him home. He was very sick but has continued to show improvement every day. He has assumed his role as the boss of the pack and is even playing with the puppy. Most importantly, he's happy.

The doctors were kind and understanding during this stressful period and allowed me to spend time with Elmer in the treatment area. The technicians were supportive and professional and I felt like they were all pulling for my dog to survive. Even the cleaning lady came up to us during a follow up visit and greeted Elmer by name.

I'm grateful that my experience had a good outcome and I'm dismayed by some of the negative reviews. We had to wait a couple of hours for a follow up visit, which was frustrating, but I realize that some others may have been made to wait while the technicians were all working on my dog during those first few critical hours. Health care is expensive for animals, too.  I never felt like they were putting money before my dog's well being. Multiple antivenom treatments, blood transfusions, medications and around the clock critical care by well-educated professionals is expensive. VCA was upfront about the costs and I'll be paying this off for a while, but I'm so thankful that they were there when I needed them.< /Review>

Everyone at VCA was not only knowledgeable and helpful, but also incredibly compassionate towards me in my messy/sorrowful state. Bought a 2015 CMax here.  Couldn't get the deal done on the first visit, but after couple weeks of follow-ups by the salesman David and Sales, was finally able to get a fair discount for a nice clean car and fair mileage.  The dealership had some great selections comparatively to other places I was shopping.  The cars here all seems well maintained, and also priced marked competitively.

I'm happy the sales team was persistent about getting the deal done.  I got the color I wanted .  David was straight forward and explained all the options and most everything well.  I was quite pleased with David's service considering after all, it's a car dealership.

Took our 2010 Ford Escape in for routine maintenance, and for a recurring Brake System Warning light (that I suspected was simply a faulty light - not an actual problem with the brakes). Routine maintenance was fine, and we paid a significant amount for the brake system check. After about two weeks, the same light came on again; always at random times. Along with that, the Tire Pressure warning light would sometimes come on. No problem with the pressure - just the light.
I went online and chatted with someone (a bot?), described the problem in detail, and they assured me someone from the dealership would call me back to arrange a re-evaluation and a fix. Never happened. I gave it another week or two and did the same thing - chatted with the bot. The bot assured me someone from the dealership would call me back, etc., etc. Never happened.
The car drives fine. Those warning lights just come on from time to time. But we've never heard back from anyone at Towne Ford. We'll likely be going elsewhere for service in the future, and if we choose to purchase another Ford, it won't be from Towne.<//Text>

<userid>109668196840828784896< /userid>< Review>
Edit: After the original review below, we ultimately decided to purchase an Audi E-tron to fill our AWD EV needs. Ford Corporates offered us (and some other Mach E reservation holders) a credit for our troubles, but still has not provide an explanation for the delays or updated timeline for the delivery of the vehicle.

Throughout the 15+ months of my reservation and 2.5 months of delays I was often frustrated by the information I was able to receive from Towne, but I recognize that they were likely struggling to get that data from Ford Corporate themselves. We were prepared to be the guinea pigs, but the repeated quality control concerns and consistently opaque communication around delays and recalls reached a breaking point when compared to the straightforward process of buying an established product line from on-the-lot inventory. Towne is not responsible for Corporate's actions, but hearing that the car is "a week or two away" for ten weeks gets pretty stale.

We genuinely hope that the Mach E is a great platform, but the disappointing rollout is costing the brand its most enthusiastic early adopters and evangelists.

=======================================
I have never tried so hard to give a company a large amount of money and found them so totally uninterested in helping me complete that transaction. I reserved a Mustang Mach E First Edition almost 15 months ago, and while I don't hold the local dealer accountable for the Ford Corporation's manufacturing struggles, Towne has been beyond useless in terms of keeping me updated on the status of the vehicle. These cars are in incredibly high demand, and dealers that fail to convert a reservation are able to mark the vehicle up significantly and still sell it in days or even hours. I can't tell if Towne is actively trying to get me to back out, or if they are just hugely indifferent about all of their $60,000+ transactions.

Over the past five months (since seeing a unit in the showroom and meeting Kevin the Internet Sales rep) I have called dozens of times in search of information on lead times, financing, and other logistics, and I have received a single return call from Kevin. Other staff who are not in Internet Sales positions have been more helpful in terms of fielding my questions and following up. When I have been able to speak directly with Kevin, he told me that "there is a lot of interest around this vehicle, so I check on these orders 2-3 times a week". The information that he is able to give is no different than what I can see using online tools, and I can check it at a single URL in seconds. I don't expect him to care about my particular car as much as I do, but if I had his VIN list (and none of his internal tools) I could check the status of every single Mach E in transit to Towne in a matter of minutes. I've also had to drive the conversation on electric vehicle rebates, on Ford's A/D/X/Z-plan pricing, and on test drives (which I still haven't had).

The vehicle's delivery window has been moved four times. That's not Towne's fault, but they have NEVER reached out to inform me of that. I have been the one driving communication with Towne, and sometimes informing them of the changes rather than the other way around. The lack of information means I have had to keep tens of thousands of dollars earmarked to pay for the vehicle since late December (the original delivery date). The latest delivery window is three days (and counting) past due. The best Towne can tell me is "we see it was due to be here, but it's not".

I don't enjoy giving bad reviews, but I'm very frustrated by the consistently bad communication and the fact that if I do walk away from this sale, Towne will profit even more by selling the car on the open market. I'm not going to buy a $60,000 car out of spite if it's not a good fit, but I do wish that Towne would give the appearance of caring about my customer experience.<//Review>

<Date>1419880263282< /Date><rate>2< /rate><Review>I would not recommend this dealership unless you are fully prepared and alert to deceptive sales strategies. I got a car I wanted, at a price I was has happy with, but I had done my homework and knew most of what was going on.

It started with an attempt at bait and switch. The Ford Focus was listed on CarGurus for $4999. A little too much based on m research, even with good mileage, and the online picture showed a visible dent. Surprise!When I get there the sticker price is $7999. So If I hadn't done my homework, I would have been bargaining from a price $3000 higher!
The car was already running.to mask a shimmy, he wanted to drive on the highway because the brakes squeal. Promised to fill up the nearly empty gas tank.
Now he gives me the CarFax--"It says there was an accident, but most people don't think that's important.--Look, it's got brand new tires!" (It's called a redirect)
I go around the car--yes, there it is, a definite dent. "Look at the hood, it's a bit out of alignment--oh the front screen come right out, and the strut that connects the headlight assembly to the frame is completely broken." I make to leave, he tries to get me to stay by suggesting that another buyer is going to snatch the car away"--I say that another buyer is going to see the same damage I see.
Fact is, I really like the car, but not at that price. He says make an offer, I lowball it. He counters, I counter again, within my predetermined range, with the condition that the brakes be checked. We start the paperwork, fine and dandy, he keeps disappearing, then comes back with, "The boss says they won't check the brakes". So he takes $300 off the price and it's now only $100 higher than my lowball offer." I also pay $75 for the right to return the car in 2 days, because I'm definitely having
my mechanic check it out. Oh, and they won't buy me any gas, either. . .Bottom line--the car is OK, needs some work, I would have returned it at the higher offer. <Pics>None</Pics>< Text>
My wife and I started coming here in late May and loved the place so much that we have come back almost every single week since, sometimes twice a week!

The wine and beer are both good, all local San Diego county breweries and wineries. But the best part, the guys pouring the drinks. We were introduced to the bartender, Joe, on our first visit. He was so awesome that we knew we had to keep coming back. His knowledge of wine is second to none. He is a professionally trained sommelier and oh man does he know his stuff. I have learned more about wine than I ever thought possible. He has such a great passion for what he does and it really shows. A few months later we were introduced to Colton, another great personality and fun person to be around. Between the two of them there is no place we'd rather be or people we'd rather be around on a Saturday night.

I think it's safe to say that if you are looking for a great place to have a drink and a good conversation, this is the place to be!< /Text>

0x809442aa1938e53b:0x4c301bffb12ed29a<//gmapID>
<UserId.>108791619027896048110< /UserId.><rate>5</rate>< Text>
Costco has the bulk items I've come to depend upon for stocking up. Buying in bulk is retail's version of Wall Street's "dollar cost averaging." You WILL have to purchase (whatever), so buying that item in bulk on a less frequent schedule makes the cost per unit less than buying lesser quantities more often. Stock up, if it fits your living arrangement. Costco has hybridized the grocery store with the big box store.

When I pass someone in the parking lot with a limited number of items in their cart, I challenge them with: You call THAT a Costco run?

Most grin and happily admit: That's only what I need today.

Costco provides those options. A quick couple of desired items (grocery, clothing, household goods, jewelry, you name it) or a proverbial cart load or two of typically dry goods to last months-long duration. Costco is the place.</Text>

< Review>
A clean and spacious costco with attentive staff, speedy checkers and an all around good vibe. Others in the area can be extremely crowded and gave more convoluted parking layouts, adding needless time to your shopping trip. This one is conveniently located next to a home depot, and many other stores and restaurants within the river park shopping center which is 2 blocks away or so. Highly recommend for an efficient shopping experience.< /Review>

<rating>4</rating>< text>
I like this Costco. The place is huge when compared to the smaller one in Clovis on the other side of town.

My complaint here, there are almost never enough registers open to support the number of people. Today was an exception, I breezed through the checkout in about 20 minutes.

Selection is great here and in some cases they have more than the other locations I shop at most frequently.

Staff: this is a hit or miss rating because you never know what you're going to get. Unlike the Clovis store where the staff are always, and I mean always, readily available and act like they are in a good mood.

I've been eyeing this TV...</text>

< review>
Costco can't be beat. My rebate on all shopping done there practically pays for the yearly fee. Maybe it's only $20 then.
I buy as much of my grocery list as I can there, before finishing at WinCo. Many items are not in bulk, so I have many choices. Staples are really cheap!

< Text>
The parking.. terrible. The lines.. terrible. The inside.. terrible. In a nutshell it could use improvement. It's difficult to maneuver inside. When you compare it to Sam's Club, it's almost a joke. This Costco is dirty, grungy, and just down right a nightmare. It's prices are not some wild thing when you actually compare product for product against Sam's Club(matter of fact Sam's is cheaper on 9/10 products). The only thing I will say, is Costco muffins are better, but that is the ONLY thing. If you're going to go here, make sure you set aside adequate time, there is no quick trip to Costco with the parking and extreme lines. I most definitely will not be letting go of my Sam's Club membership, and will be cancelling Costco for sure.</Text>

<UserId.>104679198060475051956< /UserId.>< username>
Krissy Peck<//username>
< time>
1545301287627< /time>
<Rating>3<//Rating>< Text>
I LOVE this store, BUT, I had a really infuriating experience tonight.

I shop here all the time and it's always a very quick experience. And have never bought anything really expensive, the lines are pretty short, customer service is phenomenal, And only once have I ever gone there for an item and they were out of stock. I came in around 7:00 on a Wednesday because like me, most people have day jobs.

Tonight, yes I know it's only 7 days before Christmas... I came in for a couple cheap Christmas gifts but one in particular is one of the expensive items ($179.99) that you need to get from the merchandise counter after you have paid for it....First I gave them my receipt and waited almost 20 minutes before they told me they couldn't find the item in the back room.

A few minutes later there is a girl out front taking receipts and she tells me that they need to go look through the pallets in the entire store to see if they can find it. I asked for my receipt and go load up my car with the other items that I bought and come back, took maybe 8 mins, return, give them my receipt and wait... Mind you, I ordered a large pepperoni pizza when I was at the register.

Wait for another 17 minutes before they tell me they can't find my item even though they have 19 in stock in the store.  I was told to be issued a refund and that I need to call back to see if they found out where it was. I feel like they should probably be the ones calling me at this point.

Got in line to be issued a refund which took about 10 minutes because the girl they referred me to was doing other things away from the counter. Finally got my refund and found out it takes 24 to 48 hours to be refunded.  Also I was charged $199.99 instead of the $179.99 price tag.  Picked up my pizza, hardly warm to the touch of the box and drive home. COLD upon my arrival at home.  I probably should have asked for my pizza to be comped but THAT line was about 15 people long.

I feel that there could have been a lot better communication through the process of this deal and maybe they could have held my money and called ME in the morning to tell me it was in fact there and I could pick it up...or not, Then issued me a refund.

I probably won't buy anything over $100 from Costco in the future unless it's a gift card. I know it's not the fault of those specific workers, but I was extremely tired from standing on my feet all day at work and having to wait almost an hour on my feet at the end of the day was extremely frustrating for me, there are no benches near that area. I hope that they figure out a better way to locate their inventory in the future. Having 19 boxes of this tablet available I'm sure that they weren't missing entirely.

Thanks for being a productive awesome store typically, but I hope I'm the only one that has been stuck in this situation.  I was in the store a LOT longer than intended.</Text>

Costco is how u run a business right. Me and my fami lm y have been coming to costco for many years, and not once has costco or either of the two locations we shop at  let us down. The staff is friendly and the service is excellent. You can always find unique hema from imported cheese to vintage vines and locally sourced produce. < text>
I like this Costco. The place is huge when compared to the smaller one in Clovis on the other side of town.

My complaint here, there are almost never enough registers open to support the number of people. Today was an exception, I breezed through the checkout in about 20 minutes.

Selection is great here and in some cases they have more than the other locations I shop at most frequently.

Staff: this is a hit or miss rating because you never know what you're going to get. Unlike the Clovis store where the staff are always, and I mean always, readily available and act like they are in a good mood.

I've been eyeing this TV...<//text>
